## AI Agent Reasoning

### Context
The runtime could write files through C++ fstream APIs without reliably creating
or persisting them into the opened workspace, and browser smoke coverage could
not validate the actual unpacked extension page in branded Google Chrome.

### Decisions Made
- Extracted the WASI runtime into a dedicated module and added created-file
  persistence semantics instead of patching compiler.worker.js in place.
- Returned workspace write persistence metadata so the UI can distinguish real
  disk writes from memory-only fallback and tell the user why generated files do
  not appear on disk.
- Added COOP/COEP to the extension manifest because SharedArrayBuffer support is
  required for the terminal run path and the prior warning was real.
- Updated browser smoke resolution to prefer Chrome for Testing because branded
  Google Chrome ignores --load-extension for sideloaded extensions.

### Trade-offs
- Kept richer smoke timeout diagnostics because they are high-signal for future
  browser failures, but removed temporary step-by-step debug chatter after the
  extension-page path was proven.
- Hosted fallback smoke remains available for Chrome-family environments that do
  not load unpacked extensions, but the preferred path now exercises the real
  extension page when Chrome for Testing or similar binaries are present.
